I gave this 3 forks because it is more of a "guide recipe" in my opinion. I'm not sure that it needed it, but I buttered a glass dish to bake it in. I used a little more sour cream than mayo, used olive oil mayo instead, chives in place of the marjoram, 1 large minced clove garlic instead of powder, and onion powder instead of onion salt. I mixed the mixture with a mozz and parm blend (about 1 cup) added cayenne, and baked at 375 for 20 minutes. Then I topped it with fresh parm and the cheese blend and broiled on hi for like 10 minutes until bubbly. We ate the WHOLE thing.. (me and my husband)! I served it with "Stacey's" pita chips- PERFECTO! Next time I will be adding sauteed onions and mushrooms in a bit of sherry to see how it works. Fresh spinach would be a great addition also! So much better than any restaurant!

Rating: 3
I'm not sure everyone is making this recipe as it is written. The "Hamilton" recipe everyone refers to is from a reviewer in Hamilton, Ontario as follows: I have been making a baked artichoke dip for years with rave reviews. Its very easy! 2 cups Hellman's regular mayo, 2 cups (or more) shredded asiago cheese, minced garlic (2 or 3 cloves), 14 oz. marinated artichoke hearts chopped. Mix together (can be done day before). Hollow out round loaf of bread (save innards). Put dip in hollowed out loaf and bake for 1 hour at 350 degrees. Serve with chopped bread (from the middle of the loaf and another loaf too). Its wonderful and oh so easy. Everyone will ask you for the recipe. (Hamilton, Ontario). **************************** I doubled and modified the above recipe, with rave reviews: 4 cups Hellman's regular mayo, 4 cups shredded asiago cheese, minced garlic (4-6 cloves), 28 oz. marinated artichoke hearts chopped, 1 package frozen spinach DRAINED, 2 tbsp lemon juice. Mix together (can be done day before) in a casserole dish. Top with 2 cups shredded parmesan. Bake for 75 minutes at 350 degrees. Serve with chopped bread, sliced baguette, or water crackers.

